<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="terminology" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Terminology</title>
  <p>
    The order of <m>G = (V, E) \textit{ is the number of vertices: } |V|</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    The size of <m>G = (V, E) \textit{ is the number of edges: } |E|</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    An edge <m>\{u, v\}</m> is incident with <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The degree of a vertex <m>v</m>, <m>deg(v)</m>, is the number of edges incident with <m>v</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The degree sequence of <m>G = (V, E)</m> is the list of degrees of its vertices, in increasing order.
  </p>
  <p>
    Theorem: The sum of the degrees of the vertices in a graph equals twice the size of the graph:
    <me>
      \sum_{v \in V} \deg(v) = 2|E|
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    Examples:
  </p>
  <sage>
    <input>
      graph_data = {
        1: [2, 5],
        2: [1, 5],
        3: [4],
        5: [1, 2, 7],
        6: [],
        7: [5]
    }
    
    G = Graph(graph_data)
    
    vertex_colors = {
        'grey': [1],
        'yellow': [2],
        'green': [3],
        'brown': [4],
        'magenta': [5],
        'blue': [6],
        'orange': [7]
    }
    
    G.plot(vertex_colors=vertex_colors, layout='circular')
    </input>
  </sage>
  <p>
    <me>
      |V| = 5, |E| = 6
    </me>
    <me>
      (3, 3, 2, 2, 2)
    </me>
    <me>
      \sum_{v \in V} \deg(v) = 3 + 3 + 2 + 2 + 2 = 2 \cdot 6
    </me>
  </p>
